<h2> <font color="blue"><b> Optimization and Control Seminar, Fall 2008 </b></font> </h2>

<!---------------------------------------------------------------------->
 <tr class="GreyCell">
<td><span class="InGreyCell">Thursday, Spet. 11, 2008, 12:00-1:00    </span></td>
<td align="right"><span class="InGreyCell">SOND 406</span></td></tr>

<tr class="DarkGreyCell">
<td colspan="2"><span class="InDarkGreyCell">
 Strict diagonal dominance and a Gersgorin type theorem in Euclidean Jordan algebras

 </span></td></tr>

<tr class="GreyCell">
<td><span class="InGreyCell">- Dr. Seetharam M. Gowda </span></td>
<td align="right"> </td></tr>

<tr class="GreyCell">
<td><span class="InGreyCell"> Abstract: For complex square matrices, the Levy-Desplanques theorem
asserts that a strictly diagonally dominant matrix is invertible. The
well-known
Gersgorin theorem on the location of eigenvalues is equivalent to this. In
this talk, by describing the real/spectral  eigenvalues of square
Hermitian quaternionic matrices and 3 by 3 Hermitian octonionic matrices, 
we show how to extend the Levy-Desplanques theorem  to an  object in a
Euclidean Jordan algebra when its Peirce decomposition with respect to a
Jordan frame is given. As a consequence, we present a Gersgorin type
theorem for the spectral eigenvalues of an object in a Euclidean Jordan
algebra.

   This is joint work with Melania Moldovan.


 </span></td>
<td align="right"> </td></tr>

<tr><td colspan="2">&nbsp;</td></tr>


